<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="99" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,152,467]" pageId="9" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,225,251]" pageId="9" pageNumber="99">Remarks</emphasis>
: This species was described by De Marmels (1989) from Cerro La Neblina, Rio Negro Department in Venezuela. De Marmels (2004) described the female and the larva. Pérez-Gutierrez &amp; Palacino-Rodríguez (2011) reported 
<emphasis box="[251,371,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="99">H. breweri</emphasis>
from Colombia, in Meta Department. We report this species for the first time from Guainía and Vaupés Departments.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,152,467]" pageId="9" pageNumber="99">
Males of this species have a distinctive yellow coloration on the thorax, small size (abdomen &lt;34mm) and robust cerci (
<figureCitation box="[299,375,405,431]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1602,1627]" captionTargetBox="[358,1229,489,1582]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[358,1229,489,1582]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Male cerci: H. bickorum: Mocoa, Putumayo (A) dorsal view (B) mediodorsal view (C) lateral view. Heteragrion breweri: Mitú, Vaupés (D) dorsal view (E) mediodorsal view (F) lateral view. Heteragrion calendulum: Pueblo Rico, Risaralda (G) dorsal view (H) mediodorsal view (I) lateral view. VbC: Ventro basal convexity." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3415715" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3415715/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="99">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
D–F), indeed the widest of the Colombian species in lateral view. Female is very similar to 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="99">H. bariai</emphasis>
, their differences are detailed above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
